data.content:
Yes — for simple inline constants, use `[DataRow]` directly. It's cleaner and gives better test names:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

If you need complex/non-constant data and want type safety (MSTest 3.4+), use `DynamicData` with **typed tuples**:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Summary:**

| Approach | Pros |
|----------|------|
| `[DataRow]` | Simplest; no extra property needed |
| Typed tuples | Type-safe; supports non-constants (e.g., objects, computed values) |
| `object[]` | Legacy; avoid in new code |

Use `[DataRow]` when all values are compile-time constants. Use typed tuples when you need runtime data or better type safety.
